 angle. The pan has rows of long oval slots. The PAM can is held close to the pan, and the finger presses the nozzle, releasing a visible fine mist across the metal surface. As the spraying continues, bold white text appears over the pan: first “NO CHOLESTEROL,” then “NO CALORIES,” and then “NO FAT.” Along the bottom, small fine print reads, “Maximum added 1 gram fat, 7 calories.”\n\nThe demonstration continues with cooked food on the slotted broiler pan. Several flat, browned pieces of food rest on the metal surface. A spatula slides easily under one piece and lifts it away from the pan. In the background is a plate with colorful vegetables, including red tomato slices and green garnish. The lifted piece is transferred onto the plate, suggesting it has released cleanly from the pan without sticking.\n\nThe older man appears again in the study, holding the PAM can near his face and looking at it, then back toward the viewer. He gestures toward the can with his other hand, emphasizing the product. Finally, the can is shown by itself in a hand against a softly blurred bookshelf background. Its red cap and yellow-and-red label are prominent, with “PAM” large on the front and “100 PORTIONS” visible near the bottom. To the right of the can, bold white text appears: “NO CHOLESTEROL” and “NO CALORIES,” with the same small fine print along the bottom about a maximum added 1 gram of fat and 7 calories.",
